en","1564–Female":"1564–Overleden","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1602":"1602","1601":"1601","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1622":"1622","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","13 June 1622":"13 juni 1622","1564":"1564","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","1650":"1650","about 1598":"circa 1598","1604":"1604","Hyde, North Carolina, British Colonial America":"Hyde, North Carolina, British Colonial America","Mildenhall, Forest Heath Dstrict, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1580–1640":"1580–1640","1580–1650":"1580–1650","1600–1650":"1600–1650","1601–1622":"1601–1622","1602–Male":"1602–Deceased","1604–1622":"1604–1622","1560–Male":"1560–Deceased","1564–Female":"1564–Deceased","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1602":"1602","1601":"1601","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1622":"1622","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","13 June 1622":"13 June 1622","1564":"1564","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","1650":"1650","about 1598":"about 1598","1604":"1604","Hyde, North Carolina, British Colonial America":"Hyde, North Carolina, British Colonial America","Mildenhall, Forest Heath Dstrict, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whitson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (Midlothian): from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Whiteson</i>, literally ‘white son’ or perhaps ‘son of someone named   White  ’. Occasionally, a variant of   Whiston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"White","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>white</i>, <i>wit</i> (Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’), hence a nickname for someone with white hair or a pale complexion. In some cases it is perhaps from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i>, a short form of names in <i>Hwīt-</i> (from <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’). The name may also be topographic, referring to someone who lived by a bend or curve in a river or road (from Old English <i>wiht</i> ‘bend’), the source of the placename of Great Whyte in Ramsey, Huntingdonshire (compare   Wight  ). This name is also a variant of   Wight  . The surname <i>White</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Irish and Scottish: adopted for any of several Irish and Scottish Gaelic names based on <i>bán</i> ‘white, fair’ (see   Bain   1,   McElwain  ) or <i>fionn</i> ‘fair’ (see   Finn   1). The English surname has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>de Faoite</b>.","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘white’, for example German   Weiss  , French   Blanc  , Polish <b>Białas</b> (see   Bialas  ), Slovenian   Belec  , or any other synonymous Slavic surname beginning with <i>Bel-</i>, <i>Bev-</i>, <i>Biel-</i> or <i>Bil-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Benjamin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the youngest of the twelve sons of Jacob. His mother Rachel died in giving birth to him, and in her last moments she named him <i>Benoni</i>, meaning ‘son of my sorrow’. His father, however, did not wish him to bear such an ill-omened name, and renamed him <i>Benyamin</i> (Genesis 35:16–18; 42:4). This means either ‘son of the right hand’ or more likely ‘son of the south’ (Hebrew <i>yamin</i> can also mean ‘south’), since Benjamin was the only child of Jacob born in Canaan and not in Mesopotamia to the north. Another tradition is that the second element of the name is a variant of the Hebrew plural noun <i>yamim</i>, which means ‘days’ but is used idiomatically to mean ‘year’ or ‘years’. The name would then mean ‘son of (my) old age’ and refer to the fact that Benjamin was Jacob's youngest child. In the Middle Ages the name was often given to sons whose mothers had died in childbirth. Today it has no such unfortunate associations and it grew enormously in popularity following the release of the film The Graduate (  1967 ), in which  Dustin Hoffman  played the role of  Benjamin Braddock . It is used in Scotland as an Anglicized form of Gaelic Beathan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":5,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":7,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":20,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":40,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Benjamin Whitson was born in 1580, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, his father, Benjamin Whitson, was 20 and his mother, Cathy Cox, was 17. He married Lila Maxey about 1598, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1640, in Hyde, North Carolina, British Colonial America, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1580–1640":"1580–1640","1580–1650":"1580–1650","1600–1650":"1600–1650","1601–1622":"1601–1622","1602–Male":"1602–Surnud","1604–1622":"1604–1622","1560–Male":"1560–Surnud","1564–Female":"1564–Surnud","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1602":"1602","1601":"1601","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1622":"1622","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","13 June 1622":"13. juuni 1622","1564":"1564","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","1650":"1650","about 1598":"umbes 1598","1604":"1604","Hyde, North Carolina, British Colonial America":"Hyde, North Carolina, British Colonial America","Mildenhall, Forest Heath Dstrict, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1580–1640":"1580–1640","1580–1650":"1580–1650","1600–1650":"1600–1650","1601–1622":"1601–1622","1602–